abstract: Here are six things that happened on the presidential campaign trail this week.
snippet: Here are six things that happened on the presidential campaign trail this week.
lead_paragraph: The Democratic field got a little bit smaller this week, shrinking to 19 candidates. Here’s our weekly catch-up on the 2020 election and some moments you may have missed.

abstract: Pressed about his decades-old opposition to same-sex marriage, Mr. Biden pushed back, saying he didn’t “have to evolve.”
snippet: Pressed about his decades-old opposition to same-sex marriage, Mr. Biden pushed back, saying he didn’t “have to evolve.”
lead_paragraph: CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa — Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. found himself fending off new questions about his decades-long record on lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender issues, in a testy exchange with a moderator who described his treatment of her as “condescending.”

abstract: To understand the competing Democratic health care plans, consider an elaborate home construction metaphor.
snippet: To understand the competing Democratic health care plans, consider an elaborate home construction metaphor.
lead_paragraph: Imagine the United States health care system as a sort of weird old house. There are various wings, added at different points in history, featuring different architectural styles.

abstract: Mr. Sanders has overhauled his New Hampshire state operations, as his campaign fights to maintain support in a state he won by more than 22 percentage points in 2016.
snippet: Mr. Sanders has overhauled his New Hampshire state operations, as his campaign fights to maintain support in a state he won by more than 22 percentage points in 2016.
lead_paragraph: Senator Bernie Sanders has overhauled his New Hampshire state operations five months before the primary, as his campaign fights to maintain support in a state he won by more than 22 percentage points in 2016.

abstract: Also this week, Kamala Harris releases a long-awaited plan, Elizabeth Warren wants to expand Social Security, and President Trump has a new Republican challenger.
snippet: Also this week, Kamala Harris releases a long-awaited plan, Elizabeth Warren wants to expand Social Security, and President Trump has a new Republican challenger.
lead_paragraph: A slimmed-down Democratic debate dominated this week’s campaign news — but there were other developments, too. Here’s our weekly catch-up on the 2020 election and the Democratic field.

abstract: The Democratic National Committee has announced that the next debate will be held on Oct. 15, with a possible second night on Oct. 16.
snippet: The Democratic National Committee has announced that the next debate will be held on Oct. 15, with a possible second night on Oct. 16.
lead_paragraph: The New York Times and CNN will co-host the next Democratic debate near Columbus, Ohio, on Oct. 15, with the possibility of a second round one night later depending on how many candidates meet the qualifying criteria.

headline_main: The Times and CNN Will Host the Next Democratic Debate in Ohio

abstract: Joe Biden, Kamala Harris, Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren are the leading Democrats in the presidential primary. We take a look back at their debate performances.
snippet: Joe Biden, Kamala Harris, Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren are the leading Democrats in the presidential primary. We take a look back at their debate performances.
lead_paragraph: HOUSTON — Ahead of Thursday’s debate, we looked back at how the leading Democratic candidates — Joseph R. Biden Jr., Kamala Harris, Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren — performed in the first two debates.
